<subSubSection id="209BF388FFFACA0248BDE24BFC5DCC9F" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="683EA003FFFACA0248BDE24BFC5DCC9F" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFFACA0248BDE24BFEC7CCB2" bold="true" box="[199,334,620,645]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is originated from the word Jo’bel (“zacate grande”), used by pre ‒ Hispanic people when referring to the 
<collectingCountry id="1096E093FFFACA0249A1E2B7FDFACC9F" box="[475,627,655,680]" name="Saint Kitts and Nevis" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">San Cristóbal</collectingCountry>
de las Casas valley in 
<collectingRegion id="AA456EE1FFFACA024B08E2A8FC59CC9F" box="[882,976,655,680]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="209BF388FFFACA0248BDE293FE5FCD22" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="683EA003FFFACA0248BDE293FE5FCD22" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFFACA0248BDE293FEE9CCFA" bold="true" box="[199,352,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known from three close localities in the Altos de 
<collectingRegion id="AA456EE1FFFACA024C17E293FB4ECCFA" box="[1133,1223,692,717]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
region, inside the 
<collectingRegion id="AA456EE1FFFACA0248EDE2F0FF78CCC7" box="[151,241,727,752]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
province (
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFFACA024916E2FEFEF7CCC7" box="[364,382,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">s.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="0C10DDF2FFFACA0249FDE2FFFDA7CCC7" author="Morrone" box="[391,558,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" refString="Morrone, J. (2005) Hacia una sintesis biogeografica de Mexico. Revista Mexicana de Biodiversidad, 76 (2), 207 - 252." type="journal article" year="2005">Morrone 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Its distribution may be related to pine-oak and tropical montane rain forests from this province (
<figureCitation id="F0BABC86FFFACA02490FE2DBFE40CD22" box="[373,457,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[514,1092,1007,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[470,1116,949,1856]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57 — Map of collecting localities for Colletes jobeli, C. isabelae, C. jaliscoensis and C. nigerrima. 58 — Map of collecting localities for C. solari, C. tzotzilis, C. chiaPensis, and C. guatemalensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1051949/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="209BF388FFFACA0248BDE338FC57CDB7" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="683EA003FFFACA0248BDE338FC57CDB7" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis id="5AF57C11FFFACA0248BDE338FEB2CD0F" bold="true" box="[199,315,799,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Remarks.</emphasis>
Females may have dark mandibles, reduced notch on clypeus margin, and opaque terga (probably deterioration). Some females may have malar area three times wider than longer. In males, the notch on distal margin of clypeus may be reduced and the margins of terga may be brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
